Pour the @water{300%ml} for the rice into a medium #saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @Basmati rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn
the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the #pot{} from the heat (still covered)
and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will
continue to cook in its own steam).

In the meantime, trim the @carrot{1}, then coarsely grate (no need to peel). Trim and
thinly slice the @spring onion{2}.

In a medium #bowl{}, mix together the grated carrot, spring onion, @rice vinegar{15%ml},
@sambal paste{15%g} (add less if you'd prefer things milder) and @sugar{1} for the pickle.

Set aside your 'kimchi' for later.

Trim the @green beans{80%g}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken thigh{260%g} and green beans and season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}.

Fry until golden brown on the outside and cooked through, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.
> It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Crush the @salted peanuts{25%g} in the unopened sachet using a #rolling pin{}.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Once the chicken is cooked, add the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Lower the pan to medium heat, then stir in the @gochujang paste{50%g},
@honey{15%ml} and @water{100%ml} for the sauce. Cook until the sauce has thickened,
~{4-5%minutes}.

> TIP: If your honey has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

Once the sauce has reduced, vigorously stir through the @butter{20%g} until melted.

When ready, fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and share between your bowls. Top with
the gochujang glazed chicken.

Serve with your 'kimchi' alongside and sprinkle over the salted peanuts to finish.

Enjoy!